WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.160
Few cities in Europe feel as unified as Bath,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:04.160 --> 00:00:11.200
with all those sweeping curves organizing the&nbsp;
entire city, but this harmony was not accidental.

00:00:11.200 --> 00:00:16.800
In the early eighteenth century, Bath was no more&nbsp;
than a small country market town in the southwest&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:16.800 --> 00:00:23.200
of England. Within a few decades, however, it&nbsp;
became one of the most popular, elegant, and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:23.200 --> 00:00:30.480
beautiful cities in Europe thanks to a series of&nbsp;
transformations made by an architect and his son.

00:00:30.480 --> 00:00:35.200
But long before its modern popularity&nbsp;
and architectural flourish, the history&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:35.200 --> 00:00:40.160
of Bath goes back to antiquity,&nbsp;
when it began as a Roman spa town,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:40.160 --> 00:00:46.720
renowned among ancient travelers who journeyed to&nbsp;
bathe in the sacred springs of a local goddess.

00:00:48.640 --> 00:00:54.640
After the Roman conquest of Britain, the&nbsp;
island became the province of Britannia,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:54.640 --> 00:01:02.720
with important cities like Eboracum (York) and&nbsp;
Londinium (London). Bath quickly emerged as an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:02.720 --> 00:01:07.440
important tourist destination for the&nbsp;
Romans, who named it Aquae Sulis, which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:07.440 --> 00:01:12.480
is Latin for “the waters of Sulis”, the&nbsp;
Celtic goddess that was worshiped there.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:12.480 --> 00:01:16.960
The Romans built an elaborate bath&nbsp;
complex around the hot springs,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:16.960 --> 00:01:24.080
and for a few centuries, the city thrived&nbsp;
as a center of ritual, health, and leisure.

00:01:24.080 --> 00:01:30.080
The remains of this Roman complex can still&nbsp;
be seen today, located in the center of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:30.080 --> 00:01:37.920
city. There you can see the steaming waters&nbsp;
rising from the earth, surrounded by the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:37.920 --> 00:01:45.520
stone architecture and engineering that once made&nbsp;
Aquae Sulis a destination of the ancient world.

00:01:45.520 --> 00:01:50.480
After the fall of the Roman Empire, Bath&nbsp;
began to decline and was destroyed by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:50.480 --> 00:01:56.240
barbaric tribes. The Roman street pattern and&nbsp;
buildings were lost. During the Middle Ages,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:56.240 --> 00:01:59.280
the city re-emerged as a religious town,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:59.280 --> 00:02:06.400
developing a nucleus of narrow streets and it&nbsp;
became a flourishing center of cloth production.

00:02:06.400 --> 00:02:13.840
Today, two main features of medieval Bath remain:&nbsp;
its dense network of narrow, organic streets,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:13.840 --> 00:02:19.360
and its Abbey, the architectural&nbsp;
crown of the medieval nucleus.

00:02:20.400 --> 00:02:24.320
Bath Abbey seems quite different from&nbsp;
other Gothic churches in England,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:24.320 --> 00:02:30.480
and that’s because it’s the last major church&nbsp;
built in medieval Catholic England. By the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:30.480 --> 00:02:35.200
time this abbey was being built in the&nbsp;
1500s, other European countries such as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:35.200 --> 00:02:41.040
Italy and Spain were in the midst of the High&nbsp;
Renaissance. Bath Abbey belongs entirely to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:41.040 --> 00:02:50.480
the final phase of English Gothic architecture,&nbsp;
known as the Perpendicular style. It features&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:50.480 --> 00:02:59.680
perpendicular tracery in its windows and one of&nbsp;
the finest examples of fan vaulting in England.

00:02:59.680 --> 00:03:07.200
The nave is extraordinary—it features one of the&nbsp;
most dematerialized vaults in a Gothic structure.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:07.920 --> 00:03:12.880
The piers dissolve into delicate&nbsp;
ribs that spread across the vault,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:12.880 --> 00:03:22.880
allowing thinner buttresses and larger&nbsp;
windows that flood the interior with light.

00:03:22.880 --> 00:03:29.200
Its front facade is very unique too. On&nbsp;
either side carved ladders rise upward&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:29.200 --> 00:03:35.600
with angels climbing up and down. This is a&nbsp;
representation of a passage from the Bible,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:35.600 --> 00:03:42.240
where Jacob has a dream about a ladder that&nbsp;
leads to heaven. And it’s intended to give&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:42.240 --> 00:03:47.520
the church a meaning of connection between&nbsp;
heaven and earth, and a path to salvation.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:47.520 --> 00:03:53.760
It’s a beautiful representation of the Catholic&nbsp;
theology that still defined England at the time.

00:03:53.760 --> 00:03:59.440
Details such as pierced parapets and thin&nbsp;
pinnacles enhance the sense of verticality and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:59.440 --> 00:04:12.000
lightness in the structure, making Bath Abbey one&nbsp;
of the most delicate Gothic structures in England.

00:04:18.800 --> 00:04:22.800
The city’s commercial strength&nbsp;
gradually declined and by the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:22.800 --> 00:04:28.880
end of the seventeenth century Bath&nbsp;
was no more than a quiet market town.

00:04:28.880 --> 00:04:33.680
In the late 1600s, renewed claims&nbsp;
about the healing powers of its&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:33.680 --> 00:04:39.840
hot springs began to circulate.&nbsp;
When Queen Anne visited in 1702,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:39.840 --> 00:04:44.720
the city’s reputation was restored&nbsp;
almost overnight. Aristocrats,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:44.720 --> 00:04:50.720
politicians, and members of the English&nbsp;
elite flocked there to bathe and socialize.

00:04:50.720 --> 00:04:56.880
Money began to flow in, and Bath started&nbsp;
to grow and expand over the region. It&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:56.880 --> 00:05:04.160
was at this moment that an ambitious architect&nbsp;
named John Wood, the Elder saw an opportunity.

00:05:04.160 --> 00:05:10.400
Inspired by the new urban squares being built in&nbsp;
France—particularly the Place Vendôme in Paris,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:10.400 --> 00:05:15.840
where multiple houses formed a single&nbsp;
architectural ensemble—John Wood,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:15.840 --> 00:05:22.720
the Elder planned Queen Square, northwest of&nbsp;
Bath’s medieval nucleus. In order to achieve&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:22.720 --> 00:05:28.480
that unified composition that characterized&nbsp;
French squares, he designed Queen Square to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:28.480 --> 00:05:34.240
resemble the forecourt of a palace, dominated&nbsp;
by a projecting pediment and columns on the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:34.240 --> 00:05:40.800
northern elevation. Although the facade&nbsp;
is composed of seven separate houses,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:40.800 --> 00:05:47.360
it is arranged in perfect symmetry, creating&nbsp;
the illusion of a single aristocratic residence.

00:05:47.920 --> 00:05:52.560
The houses in the side elevation step down&nbsp;
in accordance with the sloping ground,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:52.560 --> 00:05:57.040
yet maintain identical facades to preserve unity.

00:05:57.040 --> 00:06:01.280
The southern elevation has a sober&nbsp;
facade that echoes the grandeur of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:01.280 --> 00:06:04.560
the northern facade without competing with it.

00:06:04.560 --> 00:06:10.080
Wood designed only the exterior elevations,&nbsp;
allowing each owner to hire their own interior&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:10.080 --> 00:06:15.920
architect, as long as the facade adhered to&nbsp;
his master plan. With this project, John Wood&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:15.920 --> 00:06:22.800
the Elder introduced a modern sense of scale and&nbsp;
order to the irregular medieval fabric of Bath.

00:06:22.800 --> 00:06:29.760
A few years later, John Wood the Elder planned&nbsp;
King’s Circus, a major circular plaza enclosed&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:29.760 --> 00:06:36.160
by thirty-three houses. He connected the&nbsp;
Circus to Queen Square through Gay Street,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:36.160 --> 00:06:42.640
where he continued the same rhythm of houses with&nbsp;
stepped down facades along the sloping ground.

00:06:42.640 --> 00:06:49.120
For the Circus, he used the same strategy as&nbsp;
before—designing the entire elevation as a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:49.120 --> 00:06:55.920
single unified composition that defines a decorous&nbsp;
urban edge, and letting each client hire their own&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:55.920 --> 00:07:02.880
architect to design the back. The circular&nbsp;
facade is divided into three equal segments,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:02.880 --> 00:07:07.920
allowing three primary streets to&nbsp;
radiate outward from the plaza.

00:07:08.880 --> 00:07:14.560
Each house consists of three principal floors&nbsp;
with an underground basement and an attic on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:14.560 --> 00:07:20.000
top. Small yards are sunk into the ground&nbsp;
in front of the facades allowing daylight&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:24.880
into the basement level and providing the&nbsp;
houses with discrete service entrances.

00:07:25.600 --> 00:07:29.760
At the time, 18th century archaeology&nbsp;
was on the verge of rising,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:29.760 --> 00:07:36.640
and rediscovering ruins of antiquity such&nbsp;
as the ruins of Rome, Pompeii, Greece,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:36.640 --> 00:07:44.160
or Egypt. John Wood had previously&nbsp;
measured and surveyed Stonehenge,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:44.160 --> 00:07:49.920
and he became obsessed with the ancient pre-Roman&nbsp;
cultures that inhabited the area. So he applied&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:49.920 --> 00:07:57.280
the geometry of Stonehenge in his design for the&nbsp;
circus. In Stonehenge there is an outer elevated&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:57.280 --> 00:08:03.040
ring surrounded by a ditch, and an inner ring&nbsp;
formed by the stones proper. The diameter of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:03.040 --> 00:08:08.480
the space of the circus closely corresponds&nbsp;
with the diameter of Stonehenge’s outer ring,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:08.480 --> 00:08:13.920
and a ring of trees planted at the&nbsp;
center echoes the prehistoric stones.

00:08:13.920 --> 00:08:17.440
References not just to the&nbsp;
ancient civilizations of Britain,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:17.440 --> 00:08:22.880
but also to the Roman past of Bath are&nbsp;
evident in Wood’s project. The facade&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:22.880 --> 00:08:28.480
is organized in three horizontal registers&nbsp;
articulated by paired columns, each level&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:28.480 --> 00:08:35.680
employing a different classical order—Doric&nbsp;
at the base, Ionic above, and Corinthian at&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:35.680 --> 00:08:42.560
the top—creating a vertical progression&nbsp;
similar to that of the Colosseum in Rome.

00:08:42.560 --> 00:08:46.880
Like many architects of the time,&nbsp;
Wood was associated with Freemasonry,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:46.880 --> 00:08:51.280
and he carved masonic symbols into the&nbsp;
triglyphs of the lower entablature,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:51.280 --> 00:08:55.440
including allegories of knowledge&nbsp;
such as a compass drawing a circle,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:55.440 --> 00:09:04.640
a telescope, a canvas, as well as references&nbsp;
to Classical Rome and ancient civilizations.

00:09:04.640 --> 00:09:09.280
John Wood the Elder died while overseeing&nbsp;
the construction of the Circus. His work&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:09.280 --> 00:09:15.360
was continued by his son, John Wood, the Younger,&nbsp;
who, at a moment when Bath’s popularity—and demand&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:15.360 --> 00:09:22.080
for housing—was rapidly increasing, extended the&nbsp;
western axis of the Circus, and connected it to a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:22.080 --> 00:09:35.440
new residential complex: the Royal Crescent—a work&nbsp;
of true genius that redefined urban development.

00:09:35.440 --> 00:09:39.520
Whereas John Wood, the Elder conceived&nbsp;
urban form through the typical baroque&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:39.520 --> 00:09:44.640
strategy of linking architectural spaces&nbsp;
with a wide primary street defining the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:44.640 --> 00:09:49.440
urban edge and leaving nature out, John&nbsp;
Wood, the Younger tries to engage the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:49.440 --> 00:09:56.320
urban edge directly with the natural landscape.&nbsp;
He preserves his father’s innovative concept of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:56.320 --> 00:10:01.280
strictly controlling the facade design while&nbsp;
allowing different plans for the interiors.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:01.280 --> 00:10:07.200
However, instead of enclosing the space, he&nbsp;
integrated the landscape by forming a half&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:07.200 --> 00:10:15.200
ellipse with a major axis of 155 meters, built&nbsp;
around a sloping hillside. He secured a legal&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:15.200 --> 00:10:21.440
covenant ensuring that the open field to the south&nbsp;
would remain permanently unbuilt, perpetually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:21.440 --> 00:10:27.680
preserving uninterrupted views of the unspoiled&nbsp;
landscape toward the River Avon in the distance.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:27.680 --> 00:10:33.120
So the city no longer turns its back on the&nbsp;
irregular natural condition and the topography,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:33.120 --> 00:10:42.160
but completes itself with it, by blurring the edge&nbsp;
between ordered urban form and open landscape.

00:10:42.160 --> 00:10:47.200
Because the Crescent was intended to be seen&nbsp;
from a great distance across the open field,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:47.200 --> 00:10:54.240
its facade required a more monumental&nbsp;
language. So instead of stacking the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:54.240 --> 00:10:59.600
columns using the three classical orders as&nbsp;
in the Circus, Wood used the ground floor of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:59.600 --> 00:11:06.000
the houses as a base for a continuous row of&nbsp;
giant Ionic columns that frame each window&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:12.400
of the two upper floors. He also added an&nbsp;
attic floor on the top, setback behind the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:12.400 --> 00:11:18.240
cornice line to reduce its visual impact&nbsp;
and preserve the purity of the elevation.

00:11:19.040 --> 00:11:22.800
The leveled lawn in front&nbsp;
of the houses is private,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:22.800 --> 00:11:27.680
reserved exclusively for the residents,&nbsp;
and it is subtly contained by a concealed&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:27.680 --> 00:11:32.640
retaining wall known as a ha-ha—an&nbsp;
invisible boundary separating the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:32.640 --> 00:11:40.560
private garden from the steep public&nbsp;
field that slopes down towards the river.

00:11:40.560 --> 00:11:47.520
The illusion dissolves when viewed from the&nbsp;
rear—you can see how each house differs in plan,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:47.520 --> 00:11:56.160
distribution, and size, as it all depended&nbsp;
on how much facade each owner purchased.

00:11:56.160 --> 00:11:59.680
The urban expanse of Bath comes to&nbsp;
an abrupt end with the construction&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:59.680 --> 00:12:06.960
of Marlborough Buildings, which closed the&nbsp;
Royal Crescent to the northwest. From there,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:06.960 --> 00:12:12.160
the development continued uphill, forming a&nbsp;
street that would lead towards the later Lansdown&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:12.160 --> 00:12:19.440
Crescent, a multi-curved development. Designed by&nbsp;
architect John Palmer, Lansdown Crescent extends&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:19.440 --> 00:12:26.880
the idea not just to make a more complex curve,&nbsp;
but also make it move up a hill and down a valley,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:26.880 --> 00:12:34.240
creating a rhythm where space is revealed to&nbsp;
you in a way that as you approach, the volume&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:34.240 --> 00:12:45.040
becomes the open space. This crescent overlooks&nbsp;
open pastureland grazed by sheep, pairing again&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:45.040 --> 00:12:57.760
the distinctive Neoclassical architecture&nbsp;
of Bath with the landscape of rural England.

00:12:57.760 --> 00:13:01.200
Even though Bath has a medieval&nbsp;
core with a Gothic Abbey,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:01.200 --> 00:13:07.280
the architectural character of the city is for&nbsp;
the most part that introduced by John Wood.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:07.840 --> 00:13:12.480
Most buildings share the same Neoclassical&nbsp;
features that were popular in England during&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:12.480 --> 00:13:18.880
the Georgian era. This consistent architectural&nbsp;
language—with shared scale and proportion across&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:18.880 --> 00:13:29.120
the principal urban spaces—gives the city an&nbsp;
extraordinary sense of unity and cohesion.

00:13:29.120 --> 00:13:35.280
Many of these site planning projects were financed&nbsp;
by Ralph Allen, owner of the stone quarries in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:35.280 --> 00:13:41.120
the area. Allen saw in Bath an opportunity&nbsp;
to showcase the quality of his limestone,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:41.120 --> 00:13:47.840
and supplied the material for the urban projects.&nbsp;
The result is a city built almost entirely from&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:47.840 --> 00:13:55.200
the same golden limestone—a material continuity&nbsp;
that gives Bath its unmistakable character.

00:13:55.200 --> 00:13:59.040
Allen’s ambition extended beyond&nbsp;
the city itself. He commissioned&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:59.040 --> 00:14:04.880
John Wood the Elder to design Prior Park,&nbsp;
a Neo-Palladian country house overlooking&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:04.880 --> 00:14:12.160
Bath—further promoting both his stone&nbsp;
and the architectural ideals of the age.

00:14:14.320 --> 00:14:18.240
The sequence of majestic urban&nbsp;
spaces created by John Wood,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:18.240 --> 00:14:23.440
father and son, influenced countless&nbsp;
cities throughout Britain—from Edinburgh,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:23.440 --> 00:14:27.760
where the model of the Circus&nbsp;
was reinterpreted, to London,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:27.760 --> 00:14:33.760
where architect John Nash developed picturesque&nbsp;
urban compositions on an even greater scale,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:33.760 --> 00:14:40.800
as well as the many terraced houses that adopt&nbsp;
the “identical-facade” concept applied in Bath.

00:14:40.800 --> 00:14:45.520
Bath is a city designed as a&nbsp;
composition—where geometry,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:45.520 --> 00:14:54.240
landscape, and architecture converge&nbsp;
into a single, unified vision.

00:14:54.240 --> 00:14:55.200
Thanks for watching.

00:14:55.200 --> 00:14:56.320
I hope you learned.

00:14:56.320 --> 00:14:59.040
Please check out my channel as&nbsp;
I have a lot more videos about&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:59.040 --> 00:15:03.520
European cities explained as well as&nbsp;
extra content for my channel members.

00:15:03.520 --> 00:15:07.920
Also like this video to support the channel&nbsp;
and I'll see you very soon in the next episode.

00:15:07.920 --> 00:15:08.880
Goodbye!

